import java.util.HashMap;

public int maxCountTarget(int[] nums, int key) {
    HashMap<Integer, Integer> count = new HashMap<>();
    int max_count = 0;
    int max_target = -1;
    for (int i = 1; i < nums.length; ++i) {
        if (nums[i - 1] == key) {
            count.put(nums[i], count.getOrDefault(nums[i], 0) + 1);
            if (count.get(nums[i]) > max_count) {
                max_count = count.get(nums[i]);
                max_target = nums[i];
            }
        }
    }
    return max_target;
}
```

    1. Create a hash map (called `count`) to store the count of unique integers following the key.
2. Initialize `max_count` to 0 and `max_target` to -1.
3. Iterate through the array from index 1 to the end.
4. In each iteration, check if the element at the previous index is equal to the key.
5. If the previous element is equal to the key, increment the count of the current element in the hash map.
6. If the incremented count is greater than the current `max_count`, update `max_count` to the incremented count and `max_target` to the current element.
7. Return `max_target`.
